what is Eid al-Adha ?

2025-06-02T07:27:25.344298Z assistant

Eid al-Adha (Arabic: ) is one of the two major Islamic holidays, often called the "Festival of Sacrifice." It commemorates the story of the Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham) and his willingness to sacrifice his son as an act of obedience to God.

Core Meaning

  • According to Islamic tradition, God tested Ibrahim's faith by commanding him to sacrifice his son (commonly believed to be Ismail in Islam).
  • Just as he was about to do it, God intervened and provided a ram to sacrifice instead.
  • Eid al-Adha honors this moment of supreme faith, obedience, and divine mercy.

Connection to Hajj

  • It takes place during Dhu al-Hijjah, the last month of the Islamic lunar calendar.
  • Specifically, it begins on the 10th day of Dhu al-Hijjah, at the end of the Hajj pilgrimage in Mecca.
  • Hajj is one of the Five Pillars of Islam, and this holiday marks its spiritual climax.

Traditions

  • Animal sacrifice (usually sheep, goats, cows, or camels) is performed by those who can afford it, symbolizing the ram provided by God.

  • The meat is divided into three parts:

    1. One-third for the family
    2. One-third for relatives and friends
    3. One-third for the poor and needy

  • Special prayers are held at mosques

  • Charity, feasting, and community play a central role

  • Its a time for reflection, gratitude, and unity
